				<div class="ui text container">
					<p>In my tool, Sentence Grouper, I use Tensorflow.js’s universal sentence encoder package. The package comes with a pre-trained model. <strong id="strong">My first objective is building semantically-useful vectors for each sentence I give the pre-trained model.</strong> Using the package, I am able to produce useful sentence embedding vectors.
</p>
				
					<h2 class="ui sub header">Sentence embedding</h2>
					<p>
						Sentence embedding is actually conceptually similar to word embedding. It analyzes whole sentences and lets us understand the context in which words are used. We are able to understand the intention of a sentence without individually calculating the embeddings of each of its words.
					</p>
					<p>
						When using sentence embedding, sentences are placed into an n-dimensional vector space. The embeddings produced contain important features from their predecessor, word embeddings. There are various ways of highlighting the sections of our embeddings that contain key information. For example, we can utilize a technique called Principal Component Analysis (PCA).
					</p>
					
					<p>
						PCA is a dimensional reduction technique. Using PCA, we find the uniqueness of each embedding and discard similarities amongst the embeddings. I am not going to dive too deep into PCA in this post, but it is important to understand it from a high-level perspective and see how it relates to sentence embedding.
					</p>
					
					<h2 class="ui sub header">Relating vectors through cosine similarity</h2>
					
					<p>
						Cosine similarity measures the similitude between two vectors of an inner product space. It also tells us whether two vectors are pointing in roughly the same direction. We often use cosine similarity in NLP to relate text.
					</p>
					
					<p>
						Finding the cosine similarity is done by calculating the cosine angle between the two vectors. If the resulting angle of this computation is small, this suggests that the vectors are similar and that we can expect a cosine similarity closer to 1.
					</p>
					
					
